<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-combinations-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Combinations in Real Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>3.0 Statistics and Probability</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>3.1 Permutations and Combinations</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Apply permutations and combinations to real life situations</li>
                            <li>Explore the use of permutations and combinations in real life situations</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>11</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>40 minutes</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To distinguish between 'order matters' and 'grouping matters' in everyday logic.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Pose a scenario: "A coach picks a Captain and a Vice-Captain" vs "A coach picks two players to carry the ball bag." Ask students why the second scenario results in fewer unique possibilities.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <title>The Menu Planner</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A local restaurant offers a "Lunch Special" where you choose 3 side dishes from a list of 8 options (Chips, Matoke, Rice, Beans, Beef, Maize, Fruit, and Soup).
                <ol>
                    <li>If you choose Chips, Matoke, and Rice, is that a different meal than choosing Rice, Matoke, and Chips?</li>
                    <li>How many different side-dish combinations can a customer order?</li>
                    <li>If the restaurant decides to rank the sides as "Primary," "Secondary," and "Tertiary," how would the calculation change?</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight>
        <title><p>Identifying Combinations in Daily Life</p></title>
        <p>
            In real-world applications, combinations appear whenever we are forming a <strong>collection</strong> or <strong>subset</strong> where the individual items do not have unique roles or rankings.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Common Real-Life Triggers:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Sampling:</strong> Selecting a group of people for a survey or a medical trial.</li>
                <li><strong>Games of Chance:</strong> Card games (poker hands) and lottery draws where the order of cards/numbers dealt doesn't change the hand.</li>
                <li><strong>Resource Allocation:</strong> Choosing which projects to fund from a pool of proposals.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>The Mental Filter:</strong>
            <line>If swapping two selected items results in the exact same outcome, it is a <strong>Combination</strong>.</line>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <title>Medical Research</title>
        <statement>
            <p>1. A doctor needs to select 5 patients from a group of 12 volunteers to test a new vitamin. How many different groups can be formed?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since all 5 patients are receiving the same vitamin, their order of selection is irrelevant.
                <me>_{12}C_5 = \frac{12!}{5!(12-5)!} = \frac{12 \times 11 \times 10 \times 9 \times 8}{5 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1} = 792 \text{ groups.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Quality Control</title>
        <statement>
            <p>2. A factory inspector picks 3 smartphones at random from a box of 20 to check for defects. How many different samples can the inspector choose?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Testing phone A, B, and C is the same as testing C, B, and A.
                <me>_{20}C_3 = \frac{20 \times 19 \times 18}{3 \times 2 \times 1} = 1,140 \text{ possible samples.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Social Committee</title>
        <statement>
            <p>3. A company has 15 employees. They want to choose a 4-person team to plan the office party. How many different teams are possible?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <me>_{15}C_4 = \frac{15 \times 14 \times 13 \times 12}{4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1} = 1,365 \text{ teams.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A student must answer any 7 out of 10 questions on a history exam. How many ways can the student choose the questions?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>_{10}C_7 = _{10}C_3 = \frac{10 \times 9 \times 8}{6} = 120 \text{ ways.}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A pizza shop offers 10 toppings. How many different 3-topping pizzas can be made?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>_{10}C_3 = 120 \text{ pizzas.}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A jury of 12 people is to be selected from a pool of 30 citizens. How many different juries are possible?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>_{30}C_{12} = 86,493,225 \text{ juries.}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>In a deck of 52 cards, how many different 5-card hands can be dealt?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><me>_{52}C_5 = 2,598,960 \text{ hands.}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>Use "Role Play": Assign 3 students roles (Chair, Secretary) and then no roles (Team). Count the outcomes physically.</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>Focus on keyword identification (e.g., "group," "sample," "selection") vs (e.g., "rank," "arrange," "order").</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>Solve multi-step combinations (e.g., "Select 3 men from 8 and 2 women from 10 to form a committee").</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

